Domain Discovery & Horizontal Decoupling: Data Modelling, Migrating & Seeding Database Changes

Last updated: March 3rd, 2024

Topics: Data Modelling, Cardinality, Relationships, Migrations, Seeding, Leaky Abstractions

Major Topics:

By this point, we’ve been able to get the registration functionality working from end to end. But now we’ve got to hook up the popular posts feature for when we end up on the dashboard (the main page). To do this, we’ll continue down the layers of abstraction, going all the way to the database for some data modelling, migrating & seeding work.

Lesson goals

In this lesson, we’ll cover:

  • Why you’ll sometimes need to dive deep into your tools, regardless of how much they abstract away for you
  • The difference between database & domain models
  • How cardinality and relationships work in data modelling
  • How to write a migration for the new database structure
  • How to seed the database with some initial seeder data

Essential in Focus: Horizontal Decoupling

We’ve cut all the way through the system, but now we’ve got this getPopularPosts API call to implement.

We’re going to start by exploring our work at the database level first.

Because this will involve data models, migrations, and seeding — it might mean learning new things for some Code-First frontend developers.

Prefer Declarative Over Imperative Code

Now, with respect to the database and what’s within that entire abstraction (because it really is complex), if you’ve been using Prisma or some other form of ORM, you might not have had to dig too deep into the database world.

Thankfully, developer tooling companies like Prisma do a pretty good job of shielding you from the mess… for a while.

When I was a developer advocate for Apollo GraphQL, the ability to ask for the data you wanted, right from your React Components was something pretty incredible.

No more of complex data fetching logic, right? Look:

import React from 'react';
import { useQuery, gql } from '@apollo/client';

const POPULAR_POSTS_QUERY = gql`
  query GetPopularPosts {
    popularPosts {
      id
      title
      content
    }
  }
`;

const App = () => {
  const { loading, error, data } = useQuery(POPULAR_POSTS_QUERY);

  if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error: {error.message}</p>;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Popular Posts</h1>
      {data.popularPosts.map(post => (
        <div key={post.id}>
          <h2>{post.title}</h2>
          <p>{post.content}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;

And when we used Prisma to define the database schema — just telling it what we wanted, knowing that it would take the entire schema and change the database into the shape we need?

That was pretty incredible too.

backend/prisma/schema.prisma

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

datasource db {
  provider = "sqlite"
  url      = "file:./../dev.db" // Replace with your SQLite file path
}

model User {
  id        Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  email     String @unique
  firstName String
  lastName  String
  username  String
  password  String
}

Both of these examples are the beauty of what happens when we Prefer Declarative Code Over Imperative Code (design principle)

Even in your day to day, prefer this.

Perhaps the simplest example of declarative vs. imperative I can concoct is this:

// Declarative 
const numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const doubledNumbers = numbers.map((num) => num * 2);

// Imperative 
const doubledNumbersForLoop: number[] = [];
for (let i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
  doubledNumbersForLoop.push(numbers[i] * 2);
}

Using map is a lot more declarative and high level than having to use a for loop.

When you can keep your focus — the language we use — pretty high level, and focused on what we want, you “Maintain a Single Layer of Abstraction” at a time, making it easier to express and understand what it is that we want.

All Abstractions Are Leaky

The problem, as Joel Spolsky writes, is that All Abstractions Are Leaky.

What does that mean?

Well, when you’re using an abstraction like Prisma or Apollo Client, or anything else with a nice API that aims to keep things simple for you…

Expect that over time, the bubble of ignorance will burst — and you’ll be forced to dive a level deeper to understand what’s really going on behind the scenes.

This was precisely the case when Apollo dropped Apollo Client 3.

For experienced Apollo-nauts, yeah — all the power.

For less experienced, newer devs — kinda overwhelming.

Understanding is key; we can’t always hide from complexity

The point I’m trying to make here is this:

  • Horizontal Decoupling is great
  • abstraction layers are great
  • hiding complexity is great

But sometimes, we can’t hide from complexity.

Sometimes you have to learn how things actually work behind the scenes.

And this can feel like learning an entirely new domain.

In fact, I’m entirely convinced that most problems aren’t actually hard.

To me, what’s hard is just a lack of clarity.

It’s just a lack of the clarity about the domain and what’s going on.

And to me, skill is just when you have a deep level of clarity about how something works and what you’re supposed to do, so that you can make decisions more quickly.

Expect that sometimes, you’ll need to pause and learn something you didn’t intend to want to have to learn.

Just like me learning the various abstraction layers that make up shipping an interactive course experience 😅

Now let’s talk about Domain Discovery and domain models — something important to the work we’re about to do.

Essential in focus: Domain Discovery

Let’s recall what Domain Discovery is from The Metaphysics.

Every time you sit down to write code, you are working from an internal representation in your mind, of the problem at hand.

If you’re at the Code-First level, it’s likely that the logical building blocks you think about the most are things like: Components, Contexts, APIs, libraries, tools and other technical concepts.

The technical concepts are important, sure — but even more critical to the long term scalability of any project is the domain model.

But first, let’s talk about data (or database models).

Database models

To save data to the database, we need a database model.

That is, a database model is primarily concerned with the data, how we store the data, and how we represent the relationships between that data in a database.

At this level of abstraction (which is pretty low level), we’re primarily using language like tables, rows, columns, keys, indexes and all sorts of other database magic.

Domain models

But domain models — these are high level conceptual models of the problem.

And at this level, we’re concerned with the rules, relationships, and data necessary to solving the problem

If we want to write scalable code, a huge part of making that happen is ensuring we’re working from a really good domain model.

We’ll learn a

Domain model implementation

"It's developer's understanding, not your knowledge that becomes software” — Alberto Brandolini (inventor of Event Storming)

Lastly, there’s the domain model implementation, which is a fancy way to say: code created from your understanding of the problem.

We’ll expand on this idea later in Pattern-First when we chat more about Domain-Driven Design, but for now, this should enable us to move forward.

Towards a new model

We need to adjust the database, don’t we? We need to ensure that the postsAPI will work, right?

What’s new?

In order to make this work, we’ve got to represent:

posts, votes, comments, and members

Alright, and what’s the shape of the data we expect to return?

Something like this:

Example response data:

{"data":{"posts":[{"id":1,"memberId":1,"postType":"Text","title":"First post!","content":"This is bob vances first post","dateCreated":"2023-11-25T03:53:58.786Z","votes":[{"id":1,"postId":1,"memberId":1,"voteType":"Upvote"}],"memberPostedBy":{"id":1,"userId":1,"user":{"id":1,"email":"bobvance@gmail.com","firstName":"Bob","lastName":"Vance","username":"bobvance","password":"123"}},"comments":[{"id":1,"postId":1,"text":"I posted this!","memberId":1,"parentCommentId":null}]},{"id":2,"memberId":1,"postType":"Text","title":"Second post!","content":"This is bobs second post","dateCreated":"2023-11-25T03:53:58.786Z","votes":[{"id":2,"postId":2,"memberId":1,"voteType":"Upvote"},{"id":6,"postId":2,"memberId":3,"voteType":"Downvote"}],"memberPostedBy":{"id":1,"userId":1,"user":{"id":1,"email":"bobvance@gmail.com","firstName":"Bob","lastName":"Vance","username":"bobvance","password":"123"}},"comments":[{"id":2,"postId":2,"text":"Nice","memberId":2,"parentCommentId":null}]},{"id":3,"memberId":2,"postType":"Text","title":"another post","content":"This is tonys first post","dateCreated":"2023-11-25T03:53:58.786Z","votes":[{"id":3,"postId":3,"memberId":2,"voteType":"Upvote"},{"id":5,"postId":3,"memberId":1,"voteType":"Upvote"}],"memberPostedBy":{"id":2,"userId":2,"user":{"id":2,"email":"tonysoprano@gmail.com","firstName":"Tony","lastName":"Soprano","username":"tonysoprano","password":"123"}},"comments":[]},{"id":4,"memberId":2,"postType":"<https://khalilstemmler.com>","title":"Links","content":"This is a link post","dateCreated":"2023-11-25T03:53:58.786Z","votes":[{"id":4,"postId":4,"memberId":2,"voteType":"Upvote"}],"memberPostedBy":{"id":2,"userId":2,"user":{"id":2,"email":"tonysoprano@gmail.com","firstName":"Tony","lastName":"Soprano","username":"tonysoprano","password":"123"}},"comments":[]}]},"success":true}

Brilliant.

Using this, we’ll start by defining the new domain model.

Defining the model

Based on what we’ve got here, this is what I was able to draw up.

The new structure.

What’s this star stuff?

Ah, yes. Cardinality.

Let’s chat about it for a sec.

Cardinality & relationships

You may have seen these funny signs before

Cardinality is about how we document the relationships (and some rules) between the data within the model.

Typically, we have the following relationships:

  • has one / belongs to one
  • has many
  • many to many

But when we use numbers and stars, we can actually sometimes express implicit rules as well.

For example:

  • *a post is allowed to have 0 to many comments on it and that’s denoted with 0 to **
    • which implies that theoretically, a post could start out with no comments.
  • a member belongs to exactly one user and that’s denoted with 1 to 1
    • which implies that a member can’t exist unless a user does.

Now, this isn’t the best way to represent rules — I think Process Modelling, Event Storming, and using Acceptance Tests are way better ways to express and codify rules in the long-term, but at this level, it’s just a tool which can help to understand what we’re going to do.

Migrating the database

Now that we generally understand the new structure of the database, we’re going to need to apply a database migration.

What’s a migration?

It’s a script that you (or your ORM) runs to force changes to your database.

This is how we handle updating your database as the requirements change over time.

How do we do it?

If you’re using Prisma, it’s easy.

You just update your schema file.

backend/prisma/schema.prisma

// This is your Prisma schema file,
// learn more about it in the docs: <https://pris.ly/d/prisma-schema>

generator client {
  provider = "prisma-client-js"
}

datasource db {
  provider = "sqlite"
  url      = "file:./../dev.db" // Replace with your SQLite file path
}

model User {
  id        Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  email     String @unique
  firstName String
  lastName  String
  username  String
  password  String

  // Define a one-to-one relationship with Member
  member    Member?
}

model Member {
  id    Int    @id @default(autoincrement())

  user   User @relation(fields: [userId], references: [id])
  userId Int  @unique // relation scalar field (used in the `@relation` attribute above)
  posts Post[]
  votes  Vote[]
  comments  Comment[]
}

model Post {
  id             Int       @id @default(autoincrement())
  memberPostedBy Member    @relation(fields: [memberId], references: [id])
  memberId       Int       // Foreign key to the Member table
  postType       String    // 'Text' or 'Link'
  title          String
  content        String
  comments       Comment[]
  dateCreated    DateTime  @default(now())
  votes          Vote[]
}

model Comment {
  id     Int  @id @default(autoincrement())

  // Foreign key relation to the Post table
  postId Int // Foreign key to the Post table
  post   Post @relation(fields: [postId], references: [id])
  text String

  memberId        Int // Foreign key to the Member table
  memberPostedBy Member @relation(fields: [memberId], references: [id]) 

  parentCommentId    Int?
  parentComment Comment? @relation("Replies", fields: [parentCommentId], references: [id])
  replyComments Comment[] @relation("Replies")
}

model Vote {
  id            Int  @id @default(autoincrement())

  postId        Int // Foreign key to the Post table
  postBelongsTo Post @relation(fields: [postId], references: [id])

  memberId        Int // Foreign key to the Member table
  memberPostedBy Member @relation(fields: [memberId], references: [id])

  voteType String  // 'Upvote' or 'Downvote'
}

Save it, and then run the following:

npx prisma migrate dev --name <migration-name>

This will look at your current dev database, your new schema file, and create a migration you can run to update the database with:

npx prisma migrate dev

Again, if you’re using raw SQL or some other ORM like Sequelize, this could be slightly different, but this is fundamentally what we’ve got to do to push things forward.

For me, I’m using prisma so this should be straightforward (if you are too, you can see the docs here).

Generating a new ORM client

After I’ve run the migration, I need to re-run the client generation script so that I get new data model types I can use in development.

I can do that with:

npx prisma generate

This regenerates the Prisma Client code based on the schema. You can see the generated code in the node_modules/@prisma/client directory.

Now, I can access the posts and members and votes tables/data models using the client.

Seeding the database

Migrations done. Database updated, cool. But what about the data? Part of the requirements are to display data from the backend.

That means we’ll need to seed the database with some data ahead of time.

What is seeding anyway & why do we do it?

It’s loading the database with initial data. Sometimes we seed data because it’s actually just essential data that we need to make sure that the app has.

Other times it’s for testing or demos

This is the demo case.

How to seed the database

You’ll want to write a seeder script. If you’re using Prisma, here are some docs you can use to make sense of this.

You can also take a look at how I’ve done this myself.

backend/prisma/seed.ts

import { User, Post, Vote, Comment } from "@prisma/client";
import { prisma } from "../src/database";

const initialUsers: User[] = [
  {
    id: 1,
    email: "bobvance@gmail.com",
    firstName: "Bob",
    lastName: "Vance",
    username: "bobvance",
    password: '123'
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    email: "tonysoprano@gmail.com",
    firstName: "Tony",
    lastName: "Soprano",
    username: "tonysoprano",
    password: '123'
  },
  {
    id: 3,
    email: "billburr@gmail.com",
    firstName: "Bill",
    lastName: "Burr",
    username: "billburr",
    password: '123'
  },
];

const initialMemberUserIds = [
  { memberId: 1, userId: 1 },
  { memberId: 2, userId: 2 },
  { memberId: 3, userId: 3 },
];

const initialPosts: Post[] = [
  {
    id: 1,
    title: 'First post!',
    content: "This is bob vances first post",
    postType: "Text",
    dateCreated: new Date(),
    memberId: 1,
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    title: 'Second post!',
    content: "This is bobs second post",
    postType: "Text",
    dateCreated: new Date(),
    memberId: 1,
  },
  {
    id: 3,
    title: 'another post',
    content: "This is tonys first post",
    postType: "Text",
    dateCreated: new Date(),
    memberId: 2,
  },
  {
    id: 4,
    title: 'Links',
    content: "This is a link post",
    postType: "<https://khalilstemmler.com>",
    dateCreated: new Date(),
    memberId: 2,
  },
];

const initialPostVotes: Vote[] = [
  // Everyone upvotes their own first post
  { id: 1, postId: 1, voteType: 'Upvote', memberId: 1 },
  { id: 2, postId: 2, voteType: 'Upvote', memberId: 1 },
  { id: 3, postId: 3, voteType: 'Upvote', memberId: 2 },
  { id: 4, postId: 4, voteType: 'Upvote', memberId: 2 },

  // Tony's post upvoted by Bob
  { id: 5, postId: 3, voteType: 'Upvote', memberId: 1 },

  // Bob's second post downvoted by Bill
  { id: 6, postId: 2, voteType: 'Downvote', memberId: 3 },
];

const initialPostComments: Comment[] = [
  { id: 1, text: 'I posted this!', memberId: 1, postId: 1, parentCommentId: null },
  { id: 2, text: 'Nice', memberId: 2, postId: 2, parentCommentId: null }
];

async function seed() {

  for (const user of initialUsers) {
    const newUser = await prisma.user.create({
      data: user
    });

    await prisma.member.create({
      data: {
        user: {
          connect: { id: newUser.id },
        },
      },
    });
  }

  for (const post of initialPosts) {
    await prisma.post.create({
      data: post,
    });
  }

  for (const vote of initialPostVotes) {
    await prisma.vote.create({
      data: vote,
    });
  }

  for (const comment of initialPostComments) {
    await prisma.comment.create({
      data: comment,
    });
  }
}

seed();

FAQ

Wait, what's going on with the dynamic between the User and the Member? When do you create the associated member?

Ah, yes. This question.

What you're coming face to face with is a bit of domain-driven complexity that has to do with a topic called Bounded Contexts. 

Think about Google, for example. When you create an account, you get a User account.

Now think of the number of different services and applications that Google has.

Gmail, Maps, YouTube, so on and so forth. A lot, right?

Well, each of those applications are different contexts. And in those contexts, the primary way we refer to a user isn't necessarily the context of a  User. 

For example, on YouTube, there might be a ChannelOwner as a better name for a User. 

Or on Google Jobs, you have JobSeekers and Employers and CompanyOwners. Those are all domain-specific, context-specific ways to explain the concept of a User.

Really, what's 

But they all inherit the idea of a user. That means there's an association between User -> all those different types of users.

So, how should we create members then? When should we create them?

Generally, you have two main options.

  1. Create the member and the user at the same time in the same transaction
  2. Create the user first and then create the member later on, maybe when a user is trying to do something that requires the use of a Member (ie: imagine you had a Gmail account, but for years, you didn't bother with Google Dating - if that's a thing - and then one day you decide to sign up, then it creates your DatingProfile and links it to your account).

Ultimately, the simplest thing you should do in Code-First is to utilize the first option.

And you're going to want to wrap it in a transaction (which wasn't actually used here in the material, but is used in the production code for createUser).

const { user, member } = await prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
  const user = await prisma.user.create({ data: { ...userData, password: generateRandomPassword(10) } });
  const member = await prisma.member.create({ data: { userId: user.id }})
  return { user, member }
})

We'll explore this in Pattern-First, but take a look at transactions while you have a moment.
